// scrml.dev — landing page (/)
//
// Tone: honest current-state. User-ratified at S98B per the architecture
// DD §8.3 question. Matches Rule 1 + user's S95 voice on adoption
// framing ("zero adoption is a blessing in disguise right now").
//
// What this page does NOT do: marketing-flagship "three big claims with
// worked examples." That's Option (a). The user picked (b) — honest
// current-state. Read the Articles section for the why behind any claim.

<page>

    <article class="prose prose-slate max-w-3xl">

        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900">
            scrml is a language in active development.
        </h1>

        <p class="text-xl text-slate-700 mt-6 leading-relaxed">
            A full-stack language for the browser. Multi-page apps,
            real-time channels, SQL-as-syntax, state machines as
            first-class. One file format. The compiler owns the wiring.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-4">
            What works today
        </h2>

        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li>
                <strong>v0.3.0</strong> ships per-route per-role chunks,
                content-addressing, and auth as a compile-time visibility
                constraint (not a runtime check).
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>v0.2.x</strong> covers the foundational reactive
                surface: V5-strict state, validators, the auto-synthesized
                validity surface, and the pattern-matching ladder.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>scrml is post-v0.next.</strong> Engines are the UI
                centerpiece. Markup is a first-class value type. The server
                boundary disappears.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mt-12 mb-4">
            What's pending
        </h2>

        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-700">
            <li>
                Engine runtime codegen (A1c Wave 4) — the spec + parser are
                in; emission is in flight.
            </li>
            <li>
                Self-host. The scrml compiler will eventually be written in
                scrml. That's a post-v1.0 effort.
            </li>
            <li>
                The full reference surface in these docs. We're at day-1.
                Day-30 target is every Tier 1 + Tier 2 surface
                documented at MDN-rigor.
            </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="mt-12 p-6 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg bg-slate-50">
            <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                Three flagship pages are live as of today:
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-1">
                <li>
                    <a href="/reference/elements/engine"
                       class="text-blue-700 hover:text-blue-900 underline">
                        &lt;engine&gt; — state machines as a first-class element
                    </a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="/reference/elements/errors"
                       class="text-blue-700 hover:text-blue-900 underline">
                        &lt;errors of=…/&gt; — the auto-synthesized validity surface
                    </a>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <a href="/reference/contexts/sql"
                       class="text-blue-700 hover:text-blue-900 underline">
                        ?{ } — SQL as syntax; the server boundary disappears
                    </a>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
            <a href="/getting-started"
               class="px-5 py-2.5 bg-slate-900 text-white rounded-md font-medium hover:bg-slate-800">
                New here? &rarr; Get started
            </a>
            <a href="/reference"
               class="px-5 py-2.5 border border-slate-300 text-slate-900 rounded-md font-medium hover:bg-slate-50">
                Ready to dig in &rarr; Reference
            </a>
            <a href="/articles"
               class="px-5 py-2.5 border border-slate-300 text-slate-900 rounded-md font-medium hover:bg-slate-50">
                Want the why? &rarr; Articles
            </a>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mt-16 mb-4">
            Adoption framing — honest
        </h2>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed">
            scrml has near-zero adoption right now. That's a known state,
            not a problem we're papering over. LLMs have broken the
            historical friction-tipping dynamic in language adoption:
            developers who would have switched stacks in 2018 due to
            framework friction now use the same stacks with LLM assistance
            and tolerate the rough edges. The motivation to adopt a new
            language has waned.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
            scrml's bet is that it makes LLMs more efficient too — the
            same compiler-owned wiring that the developer doesn't have to
            think about is wiring the LLM doesn't have to think about.
            But until the language is serious and complete enough to be
            un-ignorable, adoption is not the expected outcome of this
            decade's pattern. We're building anyway.
        </p>

        <p class="text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mt-4">
            If that framing resonates &mdash; build something with it. If
            it doesn't &mdash; the existing stacks are fine and we don't
            begrudge anyone who stays put.
        </p>

    </article>

</page>
